{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3746771,"name":null,"username":"sh12sr","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-09-24T12:46:59.485Z","cooked":"<p>I have written a command to collect coral. The command should end when the IR sensor on the intake detects a coral, and when it does, the command finishes, but the code inside the <code>end()</code>command doesn’t run and the intake motor keeps running.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">public class Collect extends Command {
	Intake intake = Intake.getInstance();

	boolean isDone = false;

	public Collect() {
		addRequirements(intake);
	}

	@Override
	public void initialize() {
		intake.pull();
	}

	@Override
	public void execute() {
		if (intake.isHoldingCoral()) {
			isDone = true;
			// System.out.println(isDone + "    FINISHED COLLECT, SHOULD STOP");
		}
	}

	@Override
	public void end(boolean interrupted) {
		Commands.runOnce(() -&gt; new Stop(), intake);
		// new Stop().schedule();
	}

	@Override
	public boolean isFinished() {
		return isDone;
	}
}
</code></pre>
<p>when i swapped out the <code>Commands.runOnce(...)</code> with <code>new Stop().schedule()</code> it behaved as expected but could not be run again.</p>
